        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          @Damocles- There are no FFP concerns NOW, I agree, but there was the option of skirting around the rules when the deal was in it's infancy which is the morally wrong. Let me explain. Had Man City directly signed him as a free agent after he left Chelsea, there would've been no option but to pay all his wages because they have permanently signed him for X number of years depending on his contract, obviously. However, having signed for Man City-owned New York City F.C, there was the option that they (NYC) would pay a portion or all of Frank's wages therefore not counting towards City's 'Break-Even' allotment in the eyes of UEFA. The money which funds Man City also funds New York City so Lampard is getting paid by the same people regardless of who is 'officially' paying his wages. NYC would not be able to say no to the owners in regards to paying Lampard's wages or they would likely lose any investment. pt 1/2
